s an original angle to migration studies, as golden passports suggest that citizenship has become a tool for the mobility of the rich. Through close engagement with the situation in Cyprus, Passport island shows how the global market for passports is tied up with economic crises, migration, property, inequality, and European politics. The book argues that the commodification of citizenship represents a new form of offshoring by other means.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aCitizenshipzCyprus. 0aPassportszCyprus. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / General.2bisacsh  aCitizenship.  aCommodification.  aCyprus.  aInvestment migration.  aMoney laundering.  aOffshoring.  aPandora Papers.  aPassports.  aRussians.  aStatehood.1 aRakopoulos, Theodoros, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2023 eBook-Packagez9783111206455oZDB-23-MUP40uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152616737840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526167378423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526167378/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-MUPb2023